# Market Analyst (Economics Consultancy)

## Overview
Market analysts at economics consultancies apply economic theory and quantitative methods to analyze markets, competition, regulation, and policy, with particular focus on electricity and energy market modelling for clients including energy companies, regulators, infrastructure investors, and government.

## Core Responsibilities
- Building quantitative models to forecast wholesale electricity prices based on supply/demand fundamentals, fuel costs, network constraints, and policy settings across energy markets
- Analyzing electricity market structures, competition dynamics, generation investment decisions, and market efficiency to support strategic commercial and regulatory decisions
- Assessing impact of regulatory changes including network pricing, renewable energy targets, and carbon pricing on markets and various industry participants and stakeholders
- Evaluating commercial viability of energy projects such as power plants, renewable developments, and storage facilities under different market scenarios and assumptions
- Supporting expert witnesses in regulatory proceedings, competition matters, and litigation with rigorous economic analysis, data visualization, and technical documentation
- Assessing economic impacts of energy and climate policies using cost-benefit analysis and sophisticated modelling techniques to inform government and industry strategy

## Key Skills Required

### Technical & Quantitative
- Strong quantitative and analytical skills with comfort in mathematics, statistics, and optimization techniques
- Excel proficiency including complex models, solver, VBA macros, and advanced data manipulation capabilities
- Programming ability in Python for large-scale modelling and R for statistical analysis and forecasting
- Understanding of microeconomics, industrial organization, and regulatory economics theory and applications
- Energy markets knowledge including how electricity markets work, dispatch principles, and pricing mechanisms
- Data analysis and visualization skills for manipulating large datasets and creating clear, impactful charts
- Familiarity with electricity market modelling software such as PLEXOS, PowerMark, or similar specialized tools

### Interpersonal & Professional
- Clear written communication to make technical reports accessible to non-technical audiences and decision-makers
- Attention to detail and accuracy since models inform major investment decisions worth millions or billions of dollars
- Time management under deadline pressure as regulatory submission deadlines are non-negotiable and client-driven
- Intellectual curiosity about energy markets, policy developments, and the evolving energy transition landscape
- Team collaboration skills to work effectively with economists, senior consultants, and multidisciplinary project teams

### Industry Knowledge
- Understanding of National Electricity Market structure, operation, and key market participants across Australian states
- Awareness of major energy policy debates including renewable integration, grid reliability, and decarbonization pathways
- Knowledge of key institutions: AEMO, AER, AEMC, state governments, energy companies, and their respective roles and functions

## Work Mode

### Analytical & Modelling Work (65-75%)
Building and running electricity dispatch models, processing large datasets, conducting economic analysis, performing sensitivity testing, literature research, calibrating models to historical data, and validating outputs for client deliverables.

### Client Deliverables (20-25%)
Drafting report sections and regulatory submissions, creating presentations with clear visualizations, building methodology appendices, quality checking analysis for consistency, formatting documents to professional standards, and preparing materials.

### Meetings & Learning (5-10%)
Internal team meetings and project discussions, client calls and presentations (primarily observing initially), training on modelling tools and techniques, attending industry seminars and conferences, and professional development activities.

### Project Leadership (Senior levels: 25-35%)
For Senior Consultants: running consulting projects end-to-end, managing client relationships, designing sophisticated models, delegating work to junior analysts, ensuring quality control, supporting business development, and publishing thought leadership.

### Business Development & Expert Work (Director level: 40-50%)
For Directors: owning major client relationships and revenue responsibility, serving as expert witness in regulatory proceedings, driving business development, keynoting conferences, media engagement, and leading practice areas with P&L accountability.

## Workplace Culture
Project-based teams (2-5 people) working on multiple concurrent engagements balancing analytical depth with commercial pragmatism and tight deadlines in intellectually rigorous environment.

## Career Path
- Entry: Graduate Analyst (AU$65K-85K + bonus) with economics, finance, engineering, or quantitative science degree
- Progression: Consultant (2-4 yrs) → Senior Consultant (4-7 yrs) → Manager (7-10 yrs) → Director (10-15 yrs) → Partner (15+ yrs, AU$350K-600K+ plus profit share and expert witness fees AU$100K-500K+)

